      <p class="desc">
        Nalanda University was one of the world's first residential universities, founded in the 5th century CE under the Gupta dynasty. 
        With over 10,000 students and 2,000 teachers, it became a global hub of knowledge, attracting scholars from China, Korea, Sri Lanka, and beyond.
        It specialized in subjects like Buddhist philosophy, astronomy, mathematics, and medicine.
      </p>
      <p class="desc">
        Chinese traveler Xuanzang studied here. In the 12th century, it was tragically destroyed by Bakhtiyar Khilji. 
        Today, its ruins are a UNESCO World Heritage Site, and a new Nalanda University has been revived near the original location.
